:"1255–Overleden","1249–Female":"1249–Overleden","1275–1308":"1275–1308","1250–Male":"1250–Overleden","1249":"1249","1279":"1279","1255":"1255","1275":"1275","1274":"1274","1250":"1250","about 1275":"circa 1275","1308":"1308","Somersetshire, England":"Somerset, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Of, Somersetshire, England":"Somerset, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"–1279":"–1279","1255–Female":"1255–Deceased","1249–Female":"1249–Deceased","1275–1308":"1275–1308","1250–Male":"1250–Deceased","1249":"1249","1279":"1279","1255":"1255","1275":"1275","1274":"1274","1250":"1250","about 1275":"about 1275","1308":"1308","Somersetshire, England":"Somerset, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","Of, Somersetshire, England":"Somerset, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Gothart","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Goddard  .","English: occupational name for a keeper of goats, from Middle English <i>gotherde</i> (Old English <i>gāt</i> ‘goat’ + <i>hierde</i>) ‘herdsman, keeper’.","English: variant of <b>Goater</b>, with excrescent <i>-d</i>, either a topographic name for someone who lived by a stream or ditch, from Middle English <i>gote</i> ‘watercourse’ + the agent suffix <i>-(e)r</i>, or an occupational name either from Middle English <i>gotherde</i> ‘goatherd’ or from Middle English <i>goter</i> ‘goatherd’, an agent derivative of Middle English <i>got(e)</i> ‘goat’ (Old English <i>gāt</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Goddard","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from <i>Godhard</i>, a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>gōd</i> ‘good’ or <i>god</i>, <i>got</i> ‘god’ + <i>hard</i> ‘hardy, brave, strong’. The name was popular in Europe during the Middle Ages as a result of the fame of Saint Gotthard, an 11th-century bishop of Hildesheim who founded a hospice on the pass from Switzerland to Italy that bears his name. This surname is also borne by Ashkenazic Jews, presumably as an Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish surnames.","English: perhaps occasionally a variant of the occupational name   Gothard  . The two surnames may have been much confused.","French: variant of   Godard  , a cognate of 1 above."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"De","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Bright’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William De Gothart was born in Somerset, England, United Kingdom as the son of N N Gothayte and Wife Gothayte. He married Mrs William Meynell in 1274, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1279, in England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"–1279":"–1279","1255–Female":"1255–Surnud","1249–Female":"1249–Surnud","1275–1308":"1275–1308","1250–Male":"1250–Surnud","1249":"1249","1279":"1279","1255":"1255","1275":"1275","1274":"1274","1250":"1250","about 1275":"umbes 1275","1308":"1308","Somersetshire, England":"Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Of, Somersetshire, England":"Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"–1279":